This post is for my LGBTQ family and it is NOT an AD. I specifically want to speak to individuals that look a lot like me. Whether you’re gender nonconforming, non-binary or trans, going to the doctor can be a very stressful experience. I’ve gotten called sir before (not recently)and I’ve heard the horror stories from others. But no matter what, it is important for us to show up for our own health and in the process, we can always be an advocate for ourselves and try to ensure that our providers are treating us with unbiased and inclusive care. I have to say I’m with Kaiser, and every nurse has always been so attentive and mindful with how they talk to me. But please don’t let your fear, anger or anxiety keep you from your best health. 💙💙 Get your annual check ups. And when it comes to mammograms, if you are a Black person, understand that we often have dense breast tissue which means that you should ask if your provider has 3D Genius mammography. Also, remember that because of your breast tissue you may get called back for a second test and you should absolutely go get that screening. It once happened to me and everything turned out fine. But, just knowing will give you the power to make the best choices for you. #mammogram #lgbtqhealth #lgbtqheathcare #3dgeniusmammography #kaiser #hologic

#musicaltherapy Long post… I vowed this year that I would not only show the highlight reel of my life. 

So here I am. 

When the doctor walked in the room and told me that my mother had broken her hip and she would need surgery right away I broke out in tears. I already had so much on my plate. The emotions swelled. People were counting on me for deliverables, but I was consumed by everything going on with my mother. I immediately went into that mode of trying to be everyone for everybody. 

I had gotten tickets to @daniellepondermusic my new favorite artist a while ago and had resolved that I wouldn’t go because of everything that was going on. But I knew deep down that was contrary to what I actually believed. I knew that taking a break for myself was necessary. And as soon as I heard her sing the first note, I knew that I had made the right choice. During her show I laughed, I cried, and I realized that I would get through everything going on with me by never forgetting to take breaks, get rest and do whatever it takes to stay whole. 

If you don’t know about this amazing artist, please follow her, download her music, she is beyond exceptional. Thank you @daniellepondermusic 🙌🏾👏🏾💙 and thank you Byllye Avery for hipping me to this talented sister. #daniellepondermusic #danielleponder #newartist

It’s 404 Day!! And as a young native Atlien, I didn’t comprehend how important this city was and is to the rest of the country. I didn’t quite understand the importance of Black excellence and leadership because it was all that I knew. I took it for granted.  I grew up professionally in the entertainment industry. I was there as a young production asst. on set when Xscape was “Just Kicking It” and when TLC asked the important question, “What about your friends?” And over the years I have watched this city contribute greatly to the pulse for Black culture in America. But as I would evolve and transcend my entertainment roots I recognize now more than ever where Atlanta sits on the grand scale in this country. From corporate America, to politics to social justice; I can say loud and proud… Atlanta truly does Influence Everything!! This is the hardest post I’ve ever had to make. My Queen, the matriarch of our beloved family has transitioned and I know the ancestors have welcomed her home. She had a passion for life that she kept until her last days. So much of what I am I owe to her. She taught me how to love myself, my family and my community and at 3 weeks old she chose me and gave me my forever home. For that I am eternally grateful and will always try to live up to her legacy of service that she leaves behind. ✨Every day I’m always trying to make you proud Mommy!!

Still processing my mom’s transition. So grateful for memories like this one where she was in the audience and able to hear my tribute to her and to my beautiful family who was also present. This is a tough week, but I am surrounded by the legacy of love that my mother first gave to me through God. I wish I could personally reach out to each and every one of you who have called, texted, DM’d and posted. It has been an overwhelming outpouring of love and support and I thank you all. 💙🕊️

Rain was forecasted all week, but we knew Momma disliked it, so of course yesterday was the perfect sunny day for her celebration of life. 🕊️ In his words of remembrance, my brother acknowledged that we all realized early we had to share Momma with the world. Whether she was volunteering at the YMCA or Southwest Community Hospital, working with political candidates or being a surrogate mother to countless people, her heart and passion fueled her life. But she still had time for all of us. Besides the beautiful life she and my dad gave me, I thank them the most for pairing me with my amazing brother and sisters. I look up to these loving, acclaimed, humorous and compassionate humans and I am grateful for the class and grace they have exemplified during our difficult time. ✨ The unforgettable outpouring of love and support from our work, family, and friend networks is something I will always cherish. 💙✨💙

And what I meant back then is that I was the type that you wouldn’t hear me talking about any kind of activism or advocacy work in the LGBTQ space. I felt that that was for other people to do. SMH!! But as I grew up, I began to realize that I was a big part of the problem and that I needed to learn to take up more space because peoples lives were at stake. Today is the beginning of Pride month; A time where corporations waive their rainbow flags but during these times we need real action. Because did you know that in 2023 there are currently 29 states in this country without anti-discrimination laws that protect LGBTQ individuals in areas such as employment, housing, healthcare, and public accommodations. I literally did a Ted Talk about it in 2019 and sadly we are still here facing these challenges. So while I enjoy the celebration of queerness in all forms during this month, there is so much work to be done. The attacks on the trans community are rampant and its got to stop. I’m proud that I no longer sit on the sidelines and I’m even more proud of the individuals who work tirelessly every day to advance the rights of the LGBTQ community.

I’m learning so much on this journey. It’s become clear to me that how you eat is just as important as what you eat. My weight-loss has been the result of a total lifestyle change. NO MEDICATION. That’s not to knock anyone else it’s just not my journey. Below are some of the things I have incorporated into my routine. 

30 plus minutes of physical activity per day (for me it’s usually hiking, jogging, walking or strength training)

I typically eat between 11a-6p. I don’t eat at least 4 hours before bed and I get 8 hours of sleep per night. 

I limit heavier carb meals to early in the day. And I eat my protein first during meals to avoid glucose spikes.

I’ve cut out grab and go packaged food.

And finally, I’m always mindful that it’s a journey not a race. 💙💙 #takewhatyouneed #healthylifestyle #eattolive #eattherainbow #blackwomenshealth #genx

Loving these tips! 💙💫 All families can benefit from broadening the discussions at that family gatherings. 

As we gather for Thanksgiving, let’s create space for a vital conversation — our health. It’s the perfect opportunity to chat about keeping up with yearly screenings and delve into our family health history. 

Understanding the health challenges Auntie or Grandpa experienced could be incredibly beneficial for future generations. Sharing stories, warning signs, and health tips can also make a huge difference in your health outcomes.

Here’s 5 conversation starters from @blackgenesmatterinfo 

1. Start with a recent health story about a celebrity. It can be a great way to transition into personal health discussions.
2. Bring up an interesting health article or podcast you recently came across. It’s a great way to spark curiosity and open up dialogue.
3. Share your own routines, like annual doctor’s visits or screenings. It’s a simple way to see who else might be on the same track.
4. Talk about healthy recipes or lifestyle changes you’ve tried recently. This can lead to a broader discussion about preventive health measures.
5. Ask about family exercise routines or activities. It’s a lighter topic that can segue into deeper health conversations.

Let’s make this Thanksgiving a time to not only share meals, but also share knowledge that keeps us all healthier and happier. 

Be sure to visit blackgenesmatter.info for educational resources and tools to collect information about your family medical history.
